The monthly public opinion poll, carried out in April and based on a sample of 1,200 Qataris, also identified the pros to be more earnest than arguments against women’s rights.

The question was touched off late in March by a US legal specialist, Alaa Murabit, who came to Qatar to speak out about the right of women in the Middle East to vote.

She emphasized that women have to be granted the right to opt out of a marriage and have access to abortion provided by a professional health structure.

The survey result saw a masculine outlook in the majority of poll respondents for the affirmative arguments on topics including males’ roles in the family and law; while the response for the women’s arguments were far less affirmative.

Arguments among pro-men were comprehensive while there were few in numbers of those who affirmed women’s rights. Arguments among pro-men categorized as “may law allow it” (just 3.0 percent responded) likely to produce favorable arguments, trailed by “take for abides the joys of life” (7.4 percent), “wives should be included in the law” (8.6 percent), and “the punishment of open adultery” (12.8 percent).
